This is the sum of the weights of edges in the multiplex neighbourhood and for each graph layer they appear on. We add an edge weight if $e_{ij}, e_{ji} \in G$ for each network in the collection ${\cal{M}}$. We only consider edges present in both directions because the global degree is ultimately a measure of tie strength and we want to consider well-established flows between countries only. This is common practice in other contexts where tie strength is of importance such as in social networks~\cite{kwak}. We then normalise the weighted global degree by the number of possible edges $n*m$, where $n$ is the total number of nodes and $m$ is the number of networks in the multiplex collection.  We plot the cumulative degree distribution of both the weighted and unweighted global degrees in Fig.~\ref{fig:gdegs}. 

